DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(94)90044-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387894900442
KW  - International debt
KW  - Debt crisis
KW  - Official lending
AB  - Highly indebted LDCs paid very different interest rates on their external debt in 1973–1989. Countries such as Indonesia and Turkey paid rates substantially below LIBOR, while Mexico and Chile paid positive spreads. Most of the variation is explained by differences in the share of highly-subsidized official loans. Debt at floating rates was not more expensive than debt at fixed rates on average. Also, differences in the currency composition of debt did not matter much. The results suggest that evaluations of HICs policy response to the debt crisis should place more emphasis on the different burden of interest payment that countries had to bear.
ER  - 

